 television series]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated television series]]\n[[Category:American television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:Canadian children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian children's animated musical television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian computer-animated television series]]\n[[Category:Children's sketch comedy]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Mermaids in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional mermen and mermaids]]\n[[Category:Treehouse TV shows]]\n[[Category:Nick Jr. original programming]]\n[[Category:American preschool education television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian preschool education television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by DHX Media]]\n[[Category:Television series by Nelvana]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about fish]]\n", "name_user": "EvergreenFir", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Reverted edits byRealsweetie(talk) to last version by Bearcat)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bubble_Guppies"}
{"title_page": "Timothy Shanley", "text_new": "Fr '''Timothy Shanley''' (1781-1835) was an Irish [[Roman Catholic]] [[Priesthood in the Catholic Church|priest]] notable for his [[Political dissent]] against the [[Kingdom of Great Britain]] during the [[Irish Rebellion of 1798]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Illingworth|first=Ruth|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D6KYDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT85&lpg=PT85&dq=fr+shanley+westmeath&source=bl&ots=6NcWSZ8wGw&sig=ACfU3U0PLv3nHMVR3ic8sfK1h3zyRg1MKw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjNsZy2hK3oAhVB-6wKHfTdCLkQ6AEwB3oECAcQAQ|title=Little Book of Westmeath|date=2016-12-08|publisher=The History Press|isbn=978-0-7509-8155-2|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.duchas.ie/en/cbes/5009060/4982300/5120552|title=Carrick Well|website=d\u00fachas.ie|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Early Life ==\nShanley was born in Lisdessin near the village of [[Drumraney]], [[County Westmeath]] in 1781. He was one of eighteen children. He was educated at a seminary in [[Maynooth]] after taking part in an [[ambush]] near [[Tyrrellspass]] during the 1798 Rebellion.\n\nShanley was the only student in the class who did not sign the required [[Oath of Allegiance (United Kingdom)|Oath of Allegiance]] due to his belief in the Irish cause. Due to his beliefs, he was often targeted by British soldiers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.westmeathexaminer.ie/2008/08/19/rochfortbridge-church-celebrating-150-years/|title=Rochfortbridge church celebrating 150 years|website=Westmeath Examiner|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Priesthood ==\nFr Shanley was curate in [[Milltownpass]] and [[Meedin]] parish, he was then transferred to [[Slane]], [[County Meath]] for ten years, before being transferred back to Meedin. He remained there till his death in 1835.\n\nHe is buried in Carrick, near [[Dalystown, County Westmeath|Dalystown]] in County Westmeath. An annual [[mass]] is held at his gravesite on [[Good Friday]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.westmeathexaminer.ie/2011/05/18/good-friday-at-shanleys-grave/|title=Good Friday at Shanley\u2019s Grave|website=Westmeath Examiner|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:1781 births]]\n[[Category:1835 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:People from County Westmeath]]\n[[Category:United Irishmen]]\n[[Category:Irish Roman Catholic clergy stubs]]\n", "text_old": "Fr '''Timothy Shanley''' (1781-1835) was an Irish [[Roman Catholic]] [[Priesthood in the Catholic Church|priest]] notable for his [[Political dissent]] against the [[Kingdom of Great Britain]] during the [[Irish Rebellion of 1798]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Illingworth|first=Ruth|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D6KYDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT85&lpg=PT85&dq=fr+shanley+westmeath&source=bl&ots=6NcWSZ8wGw&sig=ACfU3U0PLv3nHMVR3ic8sfK1h3zyRg1MKw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjNsZy2hK3oAhVB-6wKHfTdCLkQ6AEwB3oECAcQAQ|title=Little Book of Westmeath|date=2016-12-08|publisher=The History Press|isbn=978-0-7509-8155-2|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.duchas.ie/en/cbes/5009060/4982300/5120552|title=Carrick Well|website=d\u00fachas.ie|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Early Life ==\nShanley was born in Lisdessin near the village of [[Drumraney]], [[County Westmeath]] in 1781. He was one of eighteen children. He was educated at a seminary in [[Maynooth]] after taking part in an [[ambush]] near [[Tyrrellspass]] during the 1798 Rebellion.\n\nShanley was the only student in the class who did not sign the required [[Oath of Allegiance (United Kingdom)|Oath of Allegiance]] due to his belief in the Irish cause. Due to his beliefs, he was often targeted by British soldiers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.westmeathexaminer.ie/2008/08/19/rochfortbridge-church-celebrating-150-years/|title=Rochfortbridge church celebrating 150 years|website=Westmeath Examiner|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Priesthood ==\nFr Shanley was curate in [[Milltownpass]] and [[Meedin]] parish, he was then transferred to [[Slane]], [[County Meath]] for ten years, before being transferred back to Meedin. He remained there till his death in 1835.\n\nHe is buried in Carrick, near [[Dalystown]] in County Westmeath. An annual [[mass]] is held at his gravesite on [[Good Friday]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.westmeathexaminer.ie/2011/05/18/good-friday-at-shanleys-grave/|title=Good Friday at Shanley\u2019s Grave|website=Westmeath Examiner|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:1781 births]]\n[[Category:1835 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish Roman Catholic priests]]\n[[Category:People from County Westmeath]]\n[[Category:United Irishmen]]\n[[Category:Irish Roman Catholic clergy stubs]]\n", "name_user": "PatWhelehan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePriesthood", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timothy_Shanley"}
